04417nam a22006735i 9780271079622DE-B159720210621102733.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210621t20212017pau    fo  d z      eng d  a97802710796227 a10.1515/97802710796222doi  a(DE-B1597)584507  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 4aBX8571.3b.S64 2017eb 7aREL0150002bisacsh04a284/.622300aSpeaking to Body and Soul :bInstructions for the Moravian Choir Helpers, 1785-1786 /ced. by Katherine M. Faull. 1aUniversity Park, PA : bPenn State University Press, c[2021] 4cÂ©2017  a1 online resource (200 p.) :b9 illustrations  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aPietist, Moravian, and Anabaptist Studies ;v200tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tList of Illustrations -- tPreface -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- t1 The Single Sisters' Choir -- t2 The Single Brethren's Choir -- t3 The Married Persons' Choir -- t4 The Widows' Choir -- tGlossary of Terms Specific to the Moravian Church -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aDating back to 1785, the Moravian "Instructions for the Choir Helpers" contain detailed advice for the spiritual counselors of the men, women, and children in Moravian congregations on how to address concerns about one's body and soul. In this volume, Katherine Faull presents an annotated, translated edition of the original German manuscript.In monthly "speakings"-regularly scheduled dialogues between the choir helper and individual church members to determine whether the congregant could be admitted to communion-men and women received spiritual guidance on topics as varied as the physical manifestations of puberty, sexual attraction, frequency of intercourse, infant care, and bereavement. From their founding in 1722, the Moravians were remarkable for their positive evaluation of the body; they held that the natural manifestations of masculinity and femininity were integral elements of spiritual consciousness. The "Instructions for the Choir Helpers"-which were highly confidential at the time and passed on only by permission of the church administration-reflect that philosophy, providing insights into an interpretation of the body as a holistic system that should be cared for as a vessel for the spirit.A unique resource for scholars of religious history, gender studies, and colonial American church history, Faull's translation of this fascinating set of documents provides an unprecedented glimpse into a period of foundational change in Moravian history.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 21. Jun 2021) 0aHuman bodyxReligious aspectsxMoravian ChurchvEarly works to 1800. 0aPastoral carevEarly works to 1800. 0aTheological anthropologyxMoravian ChurchvEarly works to 1800. 7aRELIGION / Christianity / History.2bisacsh1 aFaull, Katherine M., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn State University Press Complete eBook-Package 2017z978311074523840uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780271079622zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780271079622423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780271079622.jpg  a978-3-11-074523-8  Penn State University Press Complete eBook-Package 2017b2017  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK